				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Ope=
n problem on 3x+1 and x/2 functions</div>
<p>

</p>
<div role=3D"note" aria-labelledby=3D"unsolved-label-mathematics" class=3D"=
unsolved">
<div><span class=3D"unsolved-label" id=3D"unsolved-label-mathematics">Unsol=
ved problem in mathematics</span></div>
<div class=3D"unsolved-body"><div><ul><li>For even numbers, divide by 2;</l=
i><li>For odd numbers, multiply by 3 and add 1.</li></ul></div>With enough =
repetition, do all positive integers converge to 1?</div>
<div class=3D"unsolved-more"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_=
of_unsolved_problems_in_mathematics" title=3D"List of unsolved problems in =
mathematics">More unsolved problems in mathematics</a></div>
</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collatz-graph-50-no27.svg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/c/c2/Collatz-graph-50-no27.svg/250px-Collatz-graph-50-no27.svg.png" decod=
ing=3D"async" width=3D"150" height=3D"399" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"419" data-file-height=3D"1115"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directed_graph" title=3D"Directed graph">Directed=
 graph</a> showing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbit_(dyna=
mics)" title=3D"Orbit (dynamics)">orbits</a> of small numbers under the Col=
latz map, skipping even numbers. The Collatz conjecture states that all pat=
hs eventually lead to 1.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>Collatz conjecture</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-4"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> is one of the most famous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/List_of_unsolved_problems_in_mathematics" title=3D"List of unsolved proble=
ms in mathematics">unsolved problems in mathematics</a>. The <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjecture" title=3D"Conjecture">conjecture</a> =
asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually tra=
nsform every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_integer" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive integer">positive integer</a> into 1. =
It concerns <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_sequence" titl=
e=3D"Integer sequence">sequences of integers</a> in which each term is obta=
ined from the previous term as follows: if a term is <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Parity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Parity (mathematics)">eve=
n</a>, the next term is one half of it. If a term is odd, the next term is =
3 times the previous term plus 1. The conjecture is that these sequences al=
ways reach 1, no matter which positive integer is chosen to start the seque=
nce. The conjecture has been shown to hold for all positive integers up to =
<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7021236000000000000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>2.36<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=
=97</span>10<sup>21</sup></span>, but no general proof has been found.
</p><p>It is named after the mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Lothar_Collatz" title=3D"Lothar Collatz">Lothar Collatz</a>, who i=
ntroduced the idea in 1937, two years after receiving his doctorate.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The sequence of numbers involv=
ed is sometimes referred to as the <b>hailstone sequence</b>, <b>hailstone =
numbers</b> or <b>hailstone numerals</b> (because the values are usually su=
bject to multiple descents and ascents like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Hailstones" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hailstones">hailstones=
</a> in a cloud),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or as =
<b>wondrous numbers</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-7"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"P=
aul Erd=C5=91s">Paul Erd=C5=91s</a> said about the Collatz conjecture: "Mat=
hematics may not be ready for such problems."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Guy_(2004)=
_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_=
conjecture#cite_note-Guy_(2004)-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Lagarias" title=3D"Jeffrey Lagarias">Jeffrey Lagarias</=
a> stated in 2010 that the Collatz conjecture "is an extraordinarily diffic=
ult problem, completely out of reach of present day mathematics".<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Lagarias_(2010)_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Lagarias_(2010)-9"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 However, though the Collatz conjecture itself remains open, efforts to sol=
ve the problem have led to new techniques and many partial results.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Lagarias_(2010)_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Lagarias_(2010)-9"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tao_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Tao-10"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
