 without bound. No such sequence has been found.
</p><p>The smallest <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">i</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a<sub>i</sub></i> &lt; <i>=
a</i><sub>0</sub> </span> is called the <b>stopping time</b> of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>. Similarly, the sma=
llest <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> su=
ch that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a<sub>k</sub></i> =3D 1</span> is called=
 the <b>total stopping time</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">n</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lagarias_(1985)_2-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#=
cite_note-Lagarias_(1985)-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If one of the indexes <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> or <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> does not exist, we say t=
hat the stopping time or the total stopping time, respectively, is infinite=
.
</p><p>The Collatz conjecture asserts that the total stopping time of every=
