<dd>less than 10<sup>12</sup> is <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-val=
ue=3D"7011989345275647000=E2=99=A0"></span>989<span style=3D"margin-left:.2=
5em;">345</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">275</span><span style=3D=
"margin-left:.25em;">647</span></span>, which has 1348 steps.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Roosendaal_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Roosendaal-12"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (sequence =
<span class=3D"nowrap external"><a href=3D"https://oeis.org/A284668" class=
=3D"extiw" title=3D"oeis:A284668">A284668</a></span> in the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-Line_Encyclopedia_of_Integer_Sequences" title=
=3D"On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences">OEIS</a>)</dd></dl>
<p>These numbers are the lowest ones with the indicated step count, but not=
 necessarily the only ones below the given limit. As an example, <span clas=
s=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7009978065763100000=E2=99=A0"></span>=
9<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">780</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.2=
5em;">657</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">631</span></span> has 11=
32 steps, as does <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700997806=
5763000000=E2=99=A0"></span>9<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">780</span><=
span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">657</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25e=
m;">630</span></span>.
</p><p>The starting values having the smallest total stopping time with res=
pect to their number of digits (in base 2) are the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_two" title=3D"Power of two">powers of two</a>, si=
nce <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup><i>n</i></sup></span> is halved <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> times to reach 1,=
 and it is never increased.=20
</p>
