<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Supporting_arguments">Suppo=
rting arguments</h2></div>
<p>Although the conjecture has not been proven, most mathematicians<sup cla=
ss=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" tit=
le=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references=
 to reliable sources. (April 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> w=
ho have looked into the problem think the conjecture is true because experi=
mental evidence and heuristic arguments support it.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Experimental_evidence">Expe=
rimental evidence</h3></div>
<p>The conjecture has been checked by computer for all starting values up t=
o 2<sup>71</sup> =E2=89=88 <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"=
7021236000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>2.36<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;=
margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>21</sup></span>. All values teste=
d so far converge to 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Barina_13-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Bari=
na-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This computer evidence is still not rigorous proof that the conjectu=
re is true for all starting values, as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Counterexamples" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Counterexamples">count=
erexamples</a> may be found when considering very large (or possibly immens=
e) positive integers, as in the case of the disproven <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/P%C3%B3lya_conjecture" title=3D"P=C3=B3lya conjecture">=
P=C3=B3lya conjecture</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mert=
ens_conjecture" title=3D"Mertens conjecture">Mertens conjecture</a>.
</p><p>However, such verifications may have other implications. Certain con=
straints on any non-trivial cycle, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Lower_bound" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lower bound">lower bou=
nds</a> on the length of the cycle, can be proven based on the value of the=
 lowest term in the cycle. Therefore, computer searches to rule out cycles =
that have a small lowest term can strengthen these constraints.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Garner_(1981)_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Garner_(1981)-14"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Eliahou_(1993)_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Eliahou_(1993)-15"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Simons_&amp;_de_Weger_(2005)_16-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_no=
te-Simons_&amp;_de_Weger_(2005)-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"A_probabilistic_heuristic">=
A probabilistic heuristic</h3></div>
<p>If one considers only the <i>odd</i> numbers in the sequence generated b=
y the Collatz process, then each odd number is on average <span class=3D"sf=
rac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3</span><span class=
=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> of=
 the previous one.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-17"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (M=
ore precisely, the geometric mean of the ratios of outcomes is <link rel=3D=
"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035">=
<span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3</=
span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=
=81=A0</span>.) This yields a heuristic argument that every Hailstone seque=
nce should decrease in the long run, although this is not evidence against =
other cycles, only against divergence. The argument is not a proof, however=
, because it assumes that Hailstone sequences are assembled from uncorrelat=
ed probabilistic events. (It does rigorously establish that the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-adic_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"P-adic numbers">2-adic</a> extension of the Collatz process has two div=
ision steps for every multiplication step for <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Almost_all" title=3D"Almost all">almost all</a> 2-adic starting=
 values.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stopping_times">Stopping ti=
mes</h3></div>
<p>As proven by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riho_Terras_(mathe=
matician)" title=3D"Riho Terras (mathematician)">Riho Terras</a>, almost ev=
ery positive integer has a finite stopping time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjectur=
e#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Terras_(1976)_19-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite=
_note-Terras_(1976)-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other words, almost every Collatz s=
equence reaches a point that is strictly below its initial value. The proof=
 is based on the distribution of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ollatz_conjecture#As_a_parity_sequence">parity vectors</a> and uses the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Centr=
al limit theorem">central limit theorem</a>.
</p><p>In 2019, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terence_Tao" title=
=3D"Terence Tao">Terence Tao</a> improved this result by showing, using <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_density" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Logarithmic density">logarithmic density</a>, that <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_all" title=3D"Almost all">almost a=
ll</a> (in the sense of logarithmic density) Collatz orbits descend below a=
ny given function of the starting point, provided that this function diverg=
es to infinity, no matter how slowly. Responding to this work, <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quanta_Magazine" title=3D"Quanta Magazine=
">Quanta Magazine</a></i> wrote that Tao "came away with one of the most si=
gnificant results on the Collatz conjecture in decades".<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Tao_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Col=
latz_conjecture#cite_note-Tao-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#=
cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lower_bounds">Lower bounds<=
/h3></div>
<p>In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer-aided_proof" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computer-aided proof">computer-aided proof</a>, =
Krasikov and Lagarias showed that the number of integers in the interval <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">[1,<i>x</i>]</span> that eventually reach 1 is at lea=
st equal to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>0.84</sup></span> for all =
sufficiently large <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">x</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Cycles">Cycles</h2></div>
<p>In this part, consider the shortcut form of the Collatz function
