<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"k-cycles"><span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-cycles</h3></div>
<p>A <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-cyc=
le is a cycle that can be partitioned into <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i>=
</span> contiguous subsequences, each consisting of an increasing sequence =
of odd numbers, followed by a decreasing sequence of even numbers.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Simons_&amp;_de_Weger_(2005)_16-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Simons_&amp;=
_de_Weger_(2005)-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, if the cycle consists of a s=
ingle increasing sequence of odd numbers followed by a decreasing sequence =
of even numbers, it is called a <i>1-cycle</i>.
</p><p>Steiner (1977) proved that there is no 1-cycle other than the trivia=
l <span class=3D"texhtml">(1; 2)</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Steiner_(1977)_=
22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_=
conjecture#cite_note-Steiner_(1977)-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Simons (2005) used Stei=
ner's method to prove that there is no 2-cycle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture=
#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Simons and de Weger (2005) extended this proof u=
p to 68-cycles; there is no <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">k</span>-cycle up to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 68</sp=
an>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Simons_&amp;_de_Weger_(2005)_16-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-S=
imons_&amp;_de_Weger_(2005)-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hercher extended the method fur=
ther and proved that there exists no <i>k</i>-cycle with <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>k</i> =E2=89=A4 91</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hercher_(2023)_24-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conje=
cture#cite_note-Hercher_(2023)-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As exhaustive computer searc=
hes continue, larger <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span> values may be =
ruled out. To state the argument more intuitively; we do not have to search=
 for cycles that have less than 92 subsequences, where each subsequence con=
sists of consecutive ups followed by consecutive downs.<sup class=3D"noprin=
t Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wi=
kipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may need clar=
ification or removal of jargon. (September 2024)">clarification needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_formulations_of_the_c=
onjecture">Other formulations of the conjecture</h2></div>
