 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remainder" title=3D"Remainder">re=
mainder</a>). The resulting function <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">f</span> maps from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Odd_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Odd number">odd numbers</a>=
 to odd numbers. Now suppose that for some odd number <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, applying this operation <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> times yields=
 the number 1 (that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padd=
ing-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>k</i></sup></span>(<i>n</i>) =3D 1</span>). Then =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary =
number">binary</a>, the number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">n</span> can be written as the concatenation of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_(computer_science)" title=3D"String (com=
puter science)">strings</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i><sub><i>k</i></=
sub> <i>w</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> ... <i>w</i><sub>1</sub></span> =
where each <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i><sub><i>h</i></sub></span> is a =
finite and contiguous extract from the representation of <span class=3D"tex=
html"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSt=
yles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span=
 class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">=
3<sup><i>h</i></sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Colussi2011_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Colussi2011-25"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The represe=
ntation of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</spa=
n> therefore holds the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeating_d=
ecimal" title=3D"Repeating decimal">repetends</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles=
:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span cla=
ss=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">3<su=
p><i>h</i></sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>, where each repetend =
is optionally rotated and then replicated up to a finite number of bits. It=
 is only in binary that this occurs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hew2016_26-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#=
cite_note-Hew2016-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Conjecturally, every binary string <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</span> that ends with=
 a '1' can be reached by a representation of this form (where we may add or=
 delete leading '0's to&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">s</span>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_an_abstract_machine_that=
_computes_in_base_two">As an abstract machine that computes in base two</h3=
></div>
<p>Repeated applications of the Collatz function can be represented as an <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_machine" title=3D"Abstract=
 machine">abstract machine</a> that handles <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/String_(computer_science)" title=3D"String (computer science)">st=
rings</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bi=
ts</a>. The machine will perform the following three steps on any odd numbe=
r until only one <span class=3D"monospaced">1</span> remains:
</p>
<ol><li>Append <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:T=
emplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">1</span> to the (right=
) end of the number in binary (giving <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i> + 1=
</span>);</li>
<li>Add this to the original number by binary addition (giving <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i> + 1 + <i>n</i> =3D 3<i>n</i> + 1</span>);</li>
<li>Remove all trailing <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"=
mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">0</span>s (th=
at is, repeatedly divide by 2 until the result is odd).</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Example">Example</h4></div>
<p>The starting number 7 is written in base two as <link rel=3D"mw-deduplic=
ated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=
=3D"monospaced">111</span>. The resulting Collatz sequence is:
</p>
<div style=3D"font-family:monospace">
<pre>         111
        <u>111<b>1</b></u>
       1011<s>0</s>
      <u>1011<b>1</b></u>
     10001<s>0</s>
    <u>10001<b>1</b></u>
    1101<s>00</s>
   <u>1101<b>1</b></u>
  101<s>000</s>
 <u>101<b>1</b></u>
1<s>0000</s>
</pre>
</div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_a_parity_sequence">As a =
parity sequence</h3></div>
<p>For this section, consider the shortcut form of the Collatz function
