(n)=3D{\begin{cases}{\frac {n}{2}}&amp;{\text{if }}n\equiv 0\\{\frac {3n+1}=
{2}}&amp;{\text{if }}n\equiv 1\end{cases}}{\pmod {2}}.}"></span>
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml">P(...)</span> is the parity of a number, =
that is <span class=3D"texhtml">P(2<i>n</i>) =3D 0</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml">P(2<i>n</i> + 1) =3D 1</span>, then we can define the Collatz =
parity sequence (or parity vector) for a number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p<sub=
>i</sub></i> =3D P(<i>a<sub>i</sub></i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>a</i><sub>0</sub> =3D <i>n</i></span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>a</i><sub><i>i</i>+1</sub> =3D <i>f</i>(<i>a</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>)</spa=
n>.
</p><p>Which operation is performed, <span class=3D"texhtml"><link rel=3D"m=
w-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><s=
pan class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3<i>n=
</i> + 1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span>=
</span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> or <span class=3D"texhtml"><link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>n</i>=
</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span></span>, depends on the parity. The parity sequence is the =
same as the sequence of operations.
</p><p>Using this form for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>n</i>)</span=
>, it can be shown that the parity sequences for two numbers <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> and <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> will agree in the first <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> terms if a=
nd only if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</spa=
n> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> a=
re equivalent modulo <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup><i>k</i></sup></span>. T=
his implies that every number is uniquely identified by its parity sequence=
, and moreover that if there are multiple Hailstone cycles, then their corr=
esponding parity cycles must be different.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lagarias_(198=
5)_2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collat=
z_conjecture#cite_note-Lagarias_(1985)-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ter=
ras_(1976)_19-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Terras_(1976)-19"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Applying the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">f</span> function <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">k</span> times to the number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D 2<sup=
><i>k</i></sup><i>a</i> + <i>b</i></span> will give the result <span class=
=3D"texhtml">3<sup><i>c</i></sup><i>a</i> + <i>d</i></span>, where <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> is the result of=
 applying the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</=
span> function <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k<=
/span> times to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b=
</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</s=
pan> is how many increases were encountered during that sequence. For examp=
le, for <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>5</sup><i>a</i> + 1</span> there are =
3 increases as 1 iterates to 2, 1, 2, 1, and finally to 2 so the result is =
<span class=3D"texhtml">3<sup>3</sup><i>a</i> + 2</span>; for <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2<sup>2</sup><i>a</i> + 1</span> there is only 1 increase as 1=
 rises to 2 and falls to 1 so the result is <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>a</=
i> + 1</span>. When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">b</span> is <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup><i>k</i></sup> =E2=88=92 1</sp=
an> then there will be <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">k</span> rises and the result will be <span class=3D"texhtml">3<sup><=
i>k</i></sup><i>a</i> + 3<sup><i>k</i></sup> =E2=88=92 1</span>. The power =
of 3 multiplying <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
a</span> is independent of the value of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>; it depends only on the behavior of <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>. This allows o=
ne to predict that certain forms of numbers will always lead to a smaller n=
umber after a certain number of iterations: for example, <span class=3D"tex=
html">4<i>a</i> + 1</span> becomes <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>a</i> + 1</s=
pan> after two applications of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">f</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">16<i>a</i> + 3</span> be=
comes <span class=3D"texhtml">9<i>a</i> + 2</span> after four applications =
of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span>. Whet=
her those smaller numbers continue to 1, however, depends on the value of <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>.
</p>
