<p>The generalized Collatz conjecture is the assertion that every integer, =
under iteration by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">f</span>, eventually falls into one of the four cycles above or the cycle=
 0 =E2=86=92 0.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Iterating_on_rationals_with=
_odd_denominators">Iterating on rationals with odd denominators</h3></div>
<p>The Collatz map can be extended to (positive or negative) rational numbe=
rs which have odd denominators when written in lowest terms.
The number is taken to be 'odd' or 'even' according to whether its numerato=
r is odd or even. Then the formula for the map is exactly the same as when =
the domain is the integers: an 'even' such rational is divided by 2; an 'od=
d' such rational is multiplied by 3 and then 1 is added. A closely related =
fact is that the Collatz map extends to the ring of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/2-adic_integers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"2-adic in=
tegers">2-adic integers</a>, which contains the ring of rationals with odd =
denominators as a subring.
</p><p>When using the "shortcut" definition of the Collatz map, it is known=
 that any periodic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conject=
ure#As_a_parity_sequence">parity sequence</a> is generated by exactly one r=
ational.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Conversely, =
it is conjectured that every rational with an odd denominator has an eventu=
ally cyclic parity sequence (Periodicity Conjecture<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Laga=
rias_(1985)_2-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-Lagarias_(1985)-2"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>).
</p><p>If a parity cycle has length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">n</span> and includes odd numbers exactly <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> times at indices <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><sub>0</sub> &lt; =E2=8B=AF &lt; <i>k</i><sub><i=
>m</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>, then the unique rational which generates imm=
ediately and periodically this parity cycle is
