<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Optimizations">Optimization=
s</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Time=E2=80=93space_tradeoff=
"><span id=3D"Time.E2.80.93space_tradeoff"></span>Time=E2=80=93space tradeo=
ff</h3></div>
<p>The section <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjectu=
re#As_a_parity_sequence">As a parity sequence</a></i> above gives a way to =
speed up simulation of the sequence. To jump ahead <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> steps on each iteration (using t=
he <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> funct=
ion from that section), break up the current number into two parts, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> (the <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> least significant =
bits, interpreted as an integer), and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">a</span> (the rest of the bits as an integer). The res=
ult of jumping ahead <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">k</span> is given by
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;=
"><sup><i>k</i></sup></span>(2<sup><i>k</i></sup><i>a</i> + <i>b</i>) =3D 3=
<sup><i>c</i>(<i>b</i>, <i>k</i>)</sup><i>a</i> + <i>d</i>(<i>b</i>, <i>k</=
i>)</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>The values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
c</span> (or better <span class=3D"texhtml">3<sup><i>c</i></sup></span>) an=
d <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> can be=
 precalculated for all possible <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">k</span>-bit numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">b</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>d</i>(<i>b</i=
>, <i>k</i>)</span> is the result of applying the <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> function <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> times to <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>c</i>(<i>b</i>, <i>k</i>)</span> is the number of odd numbers encountered =
on the way.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For examp=
le, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 5</span>, one can jump ahead 5 =
steps on each iteration by separating out the 5 least significant bits of a=
 number and using
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>(=
0...31, 5) =3D {=E2=80=AF0, 3, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 1, 4, 1, 3, 2, 2, 3, 4, 1,=
 2, 3, 3, 1, 1, 3, 3, 2, 3, 2, 4, 3, 3, 4, 5=E2=80=AF},</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span>(0...=
31, 5) =3D {=E2=80=AF0, 2, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 20, 1, 26, 1, 10, 4, 4, 13, 40, 2=
, 5, 17, 17, 2, 2, 20, 20, 8, 22, 8, 71, 26, 26, 80, 242=E2=80=AF}.</dd></d=
l>
<p>This requires <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup><i>k</i></sup></span> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precomputation" title=3D"Precomputation"=
>precomputation</a> and storage to speed up the resulting calculation by a =
factor of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span=
>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space%E2%80%93time_tradeoff" =
title=3D"Space=E2=80=93time tradeoff">space=E2=80=93time tradeoff</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modular_restrictions">Modul=
ar restrictions</h3></div>
<p>For the special purpose of searching for a counterexample to the Collatz=
 conjecture, this precomputation leads to an even more important accelerati=
on, used by Tom=C3=A1s Oliveira e Silva in his computational confirmations =
of the Collatz conjecture up to large values of&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>. If, for some given <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>, the inequality
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;=
"><sup><i>k</i></sup></span>(2<sup><i>k</i></sup><i>a</i> + <i>b</i>) =3D 3=
<sup><i>c</i>(<i>b</i>)</sup><i>a</i> + <i>d</i>(<i>b</i>) &lt; 2<sup><i>k<=
/i></sup><i>a</i> + <i>b</i></span></dd></dl>
<p>holds for all <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
a</span>, then the first counterexample, if it exists, cannot be <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> modulo <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2<sup><i>k</i></sup></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Garner_(1981)_=
14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_=
conjecture#cite_note-Garner_(1981)-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, the first =
counterexample must be odd because <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(2<i>n</=
i>) =3D <i>n</i></span>, smaller than <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i></sp=
an>; and it must be 3 mod 4 because <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span s=
tyle=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span>(4<i>n</i> + 1) =3D 3<i>n<=
/i> + 1</span>, smaller than <span class=3D"texhtml">4<i>n</i> + 1</span>. =
For each starting value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">a</span> which is not a counterexample to the Collatz conjecture, th=
ere is a <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>=
 for which such an inequality holds, so checking the Collatz conjecture for=
 one starting value is as good as checking an entire congruence class. As <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> increases=
, the search only needs to check those residues <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> that are not eliminated by lower va=
lues of&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</s=
pan>. Only an exponentially small fraction of the residues survive.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the only survi=
ving residues mod 32 are 7, 15, 27, and 31.
</p><p>Integers divisible by 3 cannot form a cycle, so these integers do no=
t need to be checked as counterexamples.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Clay_34-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture=
#cite_note-Clay-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Syracuse_function">Syracuse=
 function</h2></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is=
 an odd integer, then <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>k</i> + 1</span> is even,=
 so <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>k</i> + 1 =3D 2<sup><i>a</i></sup><i>k</i><=
span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span=
> with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padd=
ing-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span> odd and <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>a</i> =E2=89=A5 1</span>. The <b>Syracuse function</b> is the function <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> from the s=
et <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">I</span> of po=
sitive odd integers into itself, for which <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=
(<i>k</i>) =3D <i>k</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;=
">=E2=80=B2</span></span> (sequence <span class=3D"nowrap external"><a href=
=3D"https://oeis.org/A075677" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"oeis:A075677">A07567=
7</a></span> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-Line_Encycl=
opedia_of_Integer_Sequences" title=3D"On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Seque=
nces">OEIS</a>).
</p><p>Some properties of the Syracuse function are:
</p>
<ul><li>For all <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =E2=88=88 <i>I</i></span>,=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(4<i>k</i> + 1) =3D <i>f</i>(<i>k</i>)</sp=
an>. (Because <span class=3D"texhtml">3(4<i>k</i> + 1) + 1 =3D 12<i>k</i> +=
 4 =3D 4(3<i>k</i> + 1)</span>.)</li>
<li>In more generality: For all <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i> =E2=89=A5 =
1</span> and odd <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
h</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12e=
m;"><sup><i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</sup></span>(2<sup><i>p</i></sup><i>h</i> =E2=
=88=92 1) =3D 2 =C3=97 3<sup><i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</sup><i>h</i> =E2=88=92 1=
</span>. (Here <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padding-left:=
0.12em;"><sup><i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</sup></span></span> is <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fu=
nctional power">function iteration notation</a>.)</li>
<li>For all odd <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">h=
</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(2<i>h</i> =E2=88=92 1) =E2=89=A4 =
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=
=3D"num">3<i>h</i> =E2=88=92 1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span =
class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span></li></ul>
<p>The Collatz conjecture is equivalent to the statement that, for all <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> in <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">I</span>, there exists an =
integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=89=A5 1</span> such that <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>n</=
i></sup></span>(<i>k</i>) =3D 1</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Undecidable_generalizations=
">Undecidable generalizations</h2></div>
<p>In 1972, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Horton_Conway" ti=
tle=3D"John Horton Conway">John Horton Conway</a> proved that a natural gen=
eralization of the Collatz problem is algorithmically <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undecidable_problem" title=3D"Undecidable problem">unde=
cidable</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Specifically, he considered functions of the form
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
