<p>is undecidable, by representing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Halting_problem" title=3D"Halting problem">halting problem</a> in this=
 way.
</p><p>Closer to the Collatz problem is the following <i>universally quanti=
fied</i> problem:
</p>
<dl><dd>Given <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</=
span>, does the sequence of iterates <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g<sup>k</su=
p></i>(<i>n</i>)</span> reach <span class=3D"texhtml">1</span>, for all <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> &gt; 0</span>?</dd></dl>
<p>Modifying the condition in this way can make a problem either harder or =
easier to solve (intuitively, it is harder to justify a positive answer but=
 might be easier to justify a negative one). Kurtz and Simon<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-KurtzSimon_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-KurtzSimon-36"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> proved that=
 the universally quantified problem is, in fact, undecidable and even highe=
r in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetical_hierarchy" t=
itle=3D"Arithmetical hierarchy">arithmetical hierarchy</a>; specifically, i=
t is <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=A0<span class=3D"nowrap"><span style=3D"di=
splay:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1=
.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-he=
ight:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">0</sup><br><sub style=3D"font-size:in=
herit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2</sub></span></span></s=
pan>-complete. This hardness result holds even if one restricts the class o=
f functions <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</sp=
an> by fixing the modulus <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">P</span> to 6480.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture#cite_note-37"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>Iterations of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">g</span> in a simplified version of this form, with all <span class=3D"=
mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-in=
line mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://w=
ww.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle b_{i}}">
